    <item>
      <title>A judge to weigh in on SNAP benefits. And, Trump wants to resume nuclear testing</title>
      <author>Brittney Melton</author>
      <link>https://www.npr.org/2025/10/31/g-s1-95973/up-first-newsletter-government-shutdown-snap-benefits-nuclear-testing</link>
      <comments>https://text.npr.org/2025/10/31/g-s1-95973/up-first-newsletter-government-shutdown-snap-benefits-nuclear-testing</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.npr.org/2025/10/31/g-s1-95973/up-first-newsletter-government-shutdown-snap-benefits-nuclear-testing</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 31 Oct 2025 11:01:03 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation"&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Good morning. You're reading the Up First newsletter. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/news" target="_blank"&gt;Subscribe&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; here to get it delivered to your inbox, and &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/podcasts/510318/up-first/" target="_blank"&gt;listen&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; to the Up First podcast for all the news you need to start your day.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's top stories&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tomorrow, many Americans will feel the impact of the government shutdown as SNAP food benefits will run out for about 42 million people.&lt;/strong&gt; Saturday also marks the start of enrollment on federal insurance exchanges, and premiums are expected to more than double on average. Democrats say they'll vote to reopen the government if Congress extends health care subsidies to help manage the rising costs. Yesterday, major airlines asked Congress to pass the Republicans' stopgap funding plan as air traffic controllers continue to work without pay.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-95970-1" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5000;         --source-height: 2813;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F3c%2Fb6%2F2c4ea76c4d6f9a40b47eec75d55d%2Fgettyimages-2243717347.jpg" class="img" alt="The air traffic control tower is seen at Orlando International Airport in Orlando, Florida early morning on Oct. 31. " loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 The air traffic control tower is seen at Orlando International Airport in Orlando, Florida early morning on Oct. 31. Flights at Orlando International Airport faced major delays on Oct. 30, after the Federal Aviation Administration said the airport had no certified air-traffic controllers in its tower, forcing arrivals to be halted or severely delayed amid the ongoing US government shutdown.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Miguel J. Rodriguez Carrillo/AFP via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;Democrats have traditionally been hesitant to shut down the government&lt;/strong&gt;, but don't appear to be backing down, NPR's Barbara Sprunt tells &lt;em&gt;Up First&lt;/em&gt;. Democrats seem to think Republicans will take the blame for the shutdown and not them. They are hoping &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=nx-s1-5591991:x" target="_blank"&gt;public pressure will build on the GOP&lt;/a&gt; over the expected rise in costs of health insurance premiums. Republicans say they are holding votes to fund the government and if Democrats care about funding nutrition aid and paying air traffic controllers, they would vote with them.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SNAP benefits have never been cut off due to a shutdown, and now a federal judge is stepping in to decide &lt;/strong&gt;whether to order the Trump administration to find ways to get people money to buy food. The Agriculture Department posted on its website that "the well has run dry" and stated in a memo that it doesn't have sufficient funds for SNAP benefits for next month and cannot legally use contingency funds. Democratic governors and attorneys general from about two dozen states sued, arguing that SNAP is an &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/10/30/nx-s1-5591347/snap-food-stamp-benefits-tro-court" target="_blank"&gt;entitlement that cannot be simply cut off&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;Even if the ruling comes soon, there will still be a delay in states receiving the funds they need&lt;/strong&gt;, according to NPR's Jennifer Ludden. This is because the federal government sends funding to the states before the first of the month, and then it takes days to get it onto the debit-like cards that people use. &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=nx-s1-5591991:x" target="_blank"&gt;An added complication is&lt;/a&gt; that the full SNAP funding for November is approximately $9 billion, but the administration reports that there is only about $5.5 billion in the contingency fund. Recalculating for partial payments could take weeks, resulting in people not only having to wait but also getting less money.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;President Trump announced yesterday that the U.S. would resume testing nuclear weapons for the first time in decades.&lt;/strong&gt; Some experts believe that this decision would be a major escalation and &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/10/30/nx-s1-5590818/trump-nuclear-testing" target="_blank"&gt;could disrupt the nuclear balance of power&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧&lt;strong&gt; The world's major nuclear powers have observed a testing moratorium since the 1990s as a goodwill gesture for stability after the Cold War&lt;/strong&gt;, says NPR's Geoff Brumfiel. The U.S. embarked on a program that utilizes science to ensure weapons function effectively without requiring testing. Much of that science happens in the same tunnels in the desert outside of Las Vegas where the government used to conduct nuclear testing. The U.S. has a significant technological advantage over Russia and China regarding nuclear weapons, but if those countries resume testing, they could narrow that gap, says Jon Wolfsthal at the Federation of American Scientists. There are also &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=nx-s1-5591991:x" target="_blank"&gt;environmental concerns that even if radiation is&lt;/a&gt; contained underground, the shaking would be enough to damage buildings near the site.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Deep dive&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-95409" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 8000;         --source-height: 4500;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/8000x4500+0+500/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff3%2F74%2Fe7620a1c4c579944dad6e118cc48%2Fgettyimages-2151864565.jpg" class="img" alt="Scientists are taking a second look at a drug for Alzheimer&amp;#039;s that may help patients who are particularly at risk of developing the disease." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Scientists are taking a second look at a drug for Alzheimer's that may help patients who are particularly at risk of developing the disease.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Jorg Greuel/Photodisc/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;A closer look at the effects of an experimental Alzheimer's drug called valiltramiprosate, or ALZ-801, is reviving hope that a twice-daily pill might slow down the disease in people who are at high risk of developing it. In April, researchers released results from a study involving over 300 individuals age 50 and older who were genetically predisposed to Alzheimer's disease. The overall findings indicated that those who received the drug did not perform better than those given a placebo. However, in September, a further analysis of a subgroup of 125 participants &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/shots-health-news/2025/10/29/nx-s1-5575561/alzheimers-pill-apoe4-high-risk-lecanemab-donanemab" target="_blank"&gt;revealed mild benefits for those who&lt;/a&gt; had only mild memory issues at the start of their treatment with the drug. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;💊 By one measure, the drug slowed cognitive decline by 52% in people with mild cognitive impairment. It is challenging, however, to assess the true impact of ALZ-801 due to the small sample size in the mild cognitive impairment group.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;💊 ALZ-801 could get special consideration from the Food and Drug Administration due to its potential advantages over the two drugs already on the market. The drug can be taken at home and does not cause swelling or bleeding in the brain, which often comes with monoclonal antibody treatment.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;💊 More evidence of the drug's effectiveness is expected to come from people who have continued to take the medicine after the initial 18-month study period ended, says David Watson, a co-author of the new study.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;p&gt;Read more about the &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/shots-health-news/2025/10/29/nx-s1-5575561/alzheimers-pill-apoe4-high-risk-lecanemab-donanemab" target="_blank"&gt;new findings about the Alzheimer's pill&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Weekend picks&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-94614" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2400;         --source-height: 1350;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2400x1350+0+661/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7d%2F00%2F0d4b885b4718b98948b328bf1b50%2Flk-roy-choi-bobby-fisher5.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2400x1350+0+661/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7d%2F00%2F0d4b885b4718b98948b328bf1b50%2Flk-roy-choi-bobby-fisher5.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2400x1350+0+661/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7d%2F00%2F0d4b885b4718b98948b328bf1b50%2Flk-roy-choi-bobby-fisher5.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2400x1350+0+661/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F7d%2F00%2F0